# Tirando o que nao vai ajudar a explicar a produÃ§Ã£o
getmode <- function(v) { # funcao de estimar moda
  uniqv <- unique(v)
  uniqv[which.max(tabulate(match(v, uniqv)))]
}

dad.agr <- dados %>%
  select(-domicilio) %>%
    group_by(zona) %>%
  summarise(
    veiculos = sum(veiculos*ft.exp.dom/sum(ft.exp.dom)),
    moradores = sum(moradores*ft.exp.dom/sum(ft.exp.dom)),
    viagens =sum(viagens.obs*ft.exp.dom/sum(ft.exp.dom)),
    lat = getmode(lat), long = getmode(long)) %>%
  left_join(acess, by = "zona")

dad.agr$tempo[is.na(dad.agr$tempo)] <- mean(dad.agr$tempo, na.rm = TRUE)

remove(getmode)

  ggplot() +

# verificando (in)dependencia espacial
# Indice de Moran
# To calculate Moranâ€™s I, we will need to generate a matrix of inverse distance weights
# Premissa
# For simplicity, we will treat the latitude and longitude as values on a plane rather than on a sphereâ€“our locations are close together and far from the poles.
i.dist.zo <- 1/as.matrix(dist(cbind(dad.agr$long, dad.agr$lat))) # matriz de ponderacao do inverso da distancia
diag(i.dist.zo) <- 0 # colocar zero nas diagonais
i.dist.zo[1:5, 1:5] # os 5 primeiros itens
